{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01MPLXWBhScQpeR7yTsyZdc8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019AQwTGQTKYGCYk7Y9A3sv7","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"cat >> /Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/session-retro-2026-03-28.md << 'RETRO_EOF'\n\n---\n\n# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-28 (Session 52 Update)\n\n**Timestamp:** 2026-03-28T16:30\n**Session:** 52\n**Sprint status:** COMPLETE — 74/74 stories done, 17/17 epics done\n**Productive work this session:** None. Stale state confirmed already fixed. Cost report generated.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Session Summary\n\nThis was a no-op session. All 74 stories across 17 epics were already done. The sprint-status.yaml had stale state from ralph's state reconciliation bug (stories 16-7 and 16-8 showing as `review` instead of `done`). The parent orchestrator fixed the stale state in a prior session today and confirmed ALL_DONE. This session validated that state, generated the cost report, and produced this retrospective.\n\nNo subagent work was executed. The session issues log contains entries from earlier sessions today (session 31+), which are analyzed below for completeness.\n\n## 2. Issues Analysis (from Earlier Sessions Today)\n\n### Bugs Found by Code Review Subagents\n\n| Story | HIGH | MEDIUM | LOW | Sent Back |\n|-------|------|--------|-----|-----------|\n| 16-5 (harness-run verification dispatch) | 0 | 3 (indexOf guard, DRY violation, fragile coupling) | 2 (section ordering, test brittleness) | No |\n| 16-6 (create-story tier criteria) | 1 (false-pass risk in AC2 test) | 2 (fragile markers, semantic headings) | 1 (test count docs drift) | No |\n| 16-7 (knowledge and enforcement docs) | 0 | 4 (missing tier test, weak AC8 assertions, silent empty-string fallback x2) | 2 (legacy terms out of scope) | No |\n| 16-8 (update all tests) | 0 | 0 | 3 (barrel re-export, line ref drift, missing priority test) | No |\n\n**Pattern:** Code review consistently catches MEDIUM issues and gets them fixed in the same pass. No stories were sent back for re-development. The one HIGH (false-pass risk in 16-6) was caught and fixed immediately. LOW issues were correctly deferred when out of scope.\n\n### Verification Results\n\nAll 4 stories passed verification on first attempt:\n- 16-5: 7/7 ACs passed\n- 16-6: 10/10 ACs passed (5 pre-existing BATS failures noted, unrelated)\n- 16-7: 12/12 ACs passed\n- 16-8: 12/12 ACs passed\n\n### Recurring Issues\n\n- **Ralph state corruption:** 35+ consecutive sessions with the same bug. Ralph's in-memory snapshot predates story completion, overwrites committed state on each loop iteration.\n- **Pre-existing BATS failures:** 5 failures in `all_tasks_complete` suite noted in 16-6 verification — not addressed.\n- **Legacy terminology:** `black.box` references still exist in `patches/AGENTS.md`, `patches/retro/enforcement.md`, `src/templates/verify-prompt.ts` — out of scope for current stories.\n\n## 3. Cost Analysis\n\n### Cumulative Sprint Cost (Updated)\n\n| Metric | Previous (Session 51) | Current (Session 52) | Delta |\n|--------|----------------------|---------------------|-------|\n| Total API-equivalent cost | $716.85 | $874.42 | +$157.57 |\n| Total API calls | 5,268 | 6,369 | +1,101 |\n| Average cost per story | $3.54 | $4.10 | +$0.56 |\n\nThe $157.57 increase since the last retro snapshot represents cost accrued across recent sessions (orchestrator overhead, retro generation, state fixes).\n\n### Cost by Phase\n\n| Phase | Cost | % | Observation |\n|-------|------|---|-------------|\n| verify | $467.21 | 53.4% | Dominant cost center — verification is the most expensive phase by far |\n| orchestrator | $193.95 | 22.2% | Includes 35+ no-op sessions worth of state detection and fixing |\n| retro | $102.99 | 11.8% | Retrospective generation is surprisingly expensive |\n| code-review | $43.15 | 4.9% | Efficient — catches real bugs at low cost |\n| create-story | $37.05 | 4.2% | Story creation cost is reasonable |\n| dev-story | $30.07 | 3.4% | Actual development is the cheapest phase — good ratio |\n\n### Cost by Tool\n\n| Tool | Cost | % | Note |\n|------|------|---|------|\n| Bash | $288.98 | 33.0% | Largest — test execution and git commands |\n| Read | $185.14 | 21.2% | File reading dominates due to large context windows |\n| Edit | $129.20 | 14.8% | Code modification |\n| Agent | $79.92 | 9.1% | Subagent dispatch overhead |\n| Skill | $74.64 | 8.5% | Skill invocations |\n\n### Subagent-Level Token Breakdown (from Session Issues Log)\n\nAggregated across 8 subagent runs (4 code reviews + 4 verifications) from earlier today:\n\n| Metric | Code Reviews (4) | Verifications (4) | Total |\n|--------|-----------------|-------------------|-------|\n| Total tool calls | 86 | 60 | 146 |\n| Bash calls | 24 | 31 | 55 |\n| Read calls | 37 | 20 | 57 |\n| Grep calls | 21 | 12 | 33 |\n| Edit calls | 11 | 3 | 14 |\n\n**Key observations from subagent token reports:**\n- **Repeated file reads:** `harness-run.md` was read 8 times across the 16-5 code review and verification subagents (5 + 3). A single cached read would suffice.\n- **Redundant test runs:** 3 of 4 verification subagents ran `npm test` twice (once full, once filtered). Estimated waste: ~170 lines of redundant output per verification.\n- **Code review is lean:** Average 21.5 tool calls per review. Most reads were unique files (10-14 unique per review).\n- **Verification is Bash-heavy:** 7-10 Bash calls per verification vs 3-8 for code reviews. Verifications spend most tokens on test execution output.\n\n### \"Unknown\" Cost Bucket\n\nThe `unknown` story bucket remains the largest at $226.45 (25.9%). This likely represents orchestrator overhead, state management, retro generation, and no-op session costs that are not attributed to any specific story.\n\n## 4. What Went Well\n\n- **Sprint complete: 74/74 stories, 17/17 epics.** Full delivery.\n- **Code review quality:** Caught 1 HIGH, 9 MEDIUM bugs across 4 stories. All MEDIUM+ fixed in the same pass. Zero stories sent back for rework.\n- **First-pass verification:** All 4 stories passed on first attempt. 41/41 total ACs passed.\n- **Coverage maintained:** 96.85% overall, all 158 files above 80% floor throughout.\n- **Cost efficiency for actual development:** dev-story phase is only 3.4% of total cost. The harness invests heavily in quality gates (verify + code-review = 58.3%) which is the correct trade-off.\n\n## 5. What Went Wrong\n\n- **Ralph state corruption (P0):** 35+ consecutive no-op sessions caused by the same in-memory state overwrite bug. Ralph's `status.json` still shows `stories_completed: 70` and `stories_remaining: 4`. Every session burns orchestrator tokens detecting and fixing this.\n- **No sprint-complete exit:** Ralph has no condition to stop looping when all stories are done, causing infinite no-op sessions.\n- **Cost waste from no-ops:** Estimated $150-250 spent on orchestrator overhead across 35+ sessions that did zero productive work.\n- **\"Unknown\" cost attribution:** 25.9% of total cost ($226.45) is unattributed. Without knowing what drives this, optimization is blind.\n- **Retro cost creep:** At $102.99 (11.8%), retrospective generation is expensive relative to actual development ($30.07). The retro file is now 4,491 lines — each new retro pays to read the entire file via context window.\n\n## 6. Lessons Learned\n\n- **State writes need monotonic versioning.** Ralph's read-modify-write loop without version checking is the textbook example of a lost-update bug. Every state write should include a version counter and reject stale writes.\n- **Sprint-complete must be a hard exit.** Once all stories are `done`, the orchestrator should exit immediately — not enter another loop iteration that loads stale state and \"fixes\" it again.\n- **Retro file growth is a cost multiplier.** A 4,491-line retro file means every subsequent retro pays for the full context. Consider archiving per-session retros into separate files or using a rolling window.\n- **Subagent guidelines should mandate single test capture.** Three out of four verification subagents ran `npm test` twice. A one-line guideline (\"capture test output once, filter from capture\") would save ~170 lines of output per verification.\n- **File read deduplication matters.** `harness-run.md` was read 8 times across two subagents working on the same story. A shared read cache or explicit \"read once, reference by line\" pattern would reduce this.\n\n## 7. Action Items\n\n| Priority | Action | Status |\n|----------|--------|--------|\n| **P0** | Fix Ralph state corruption — add compare-and-swap or monotonic version to state writes | CRITICAL — 35+ occurrences, estimated $150-250 waste |\n| **P0** | Add sprint-complete exit condition to Ralph's main loop | CRITICAL — stops burning sessions |\n| **P0** | Sprint is complete. Plan next sprint or close out. | CARRY FORWARD |\n| **P1** | Attribute the \"unknown\" cost bucket ($226.45, 25.9%) to specific phases/activities | CARRY FORWARD |\n| **P1** | Archive retro file — split into per-session files or implement rolling window to stop context growth | NEW |\n| **P2** | Add subagent guideline: capture test output once, grep from capture | CARRY FORWARD — 3/4 verifications ran npm test twice |\n| **P2** | Add subagent guideline: deduplicate file reads across review+verification for same story | NEW |\n| **P2** | Fix 5 pre-existing BATS failures in all_tasks_complete suite | CARRY FORWARD |\n| **P3** | Clean up legacy `black.box` references in patches/templates | CARRY FORWARD |\n| **P3** | Clean up `1-1-foo` phantom story from tracking data ($24.35 attributed cost) | CARRY FORWARD |\nRETRO_EOF","description":"Append retrospective to existing retro file"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":779,"cache_read_input_tokens":25229,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":779,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_014XSrysGGxcC8uucVkNsuL5","session_id":"1a7a6ebc-c4c8-4915-89a8-1d1ede2eb61d","uuid":"083030bb-a08f-47da-988c-e7c74bc01515"}
